{"cursor":"9052","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nIn group theory, a 'nilpotent group' is a group that is \"almost abelian\". This\nidea is motivated by the fact that nilpotent groups are solvable, and for finite\nnilpotent groups, two elements having relatively prime orders must commute. It\nis also true that finite nilpotent groups are supersolvable.\n\nNilpotent groups arise in Galois theory, as well as in the classification of\ngroups. They also appear prominently in the classification of Lie groups.\n\nAnalogous terms are used for Lie algebras (using the Lie bracket) including\n'[[nilpotent Lie algebra|nilpotent]]', 'lower central series', and 'upper\ncentral series'.\n","linknr":270,"url":"Nilpotent_group","recorded":1362685143,"links":22,"instances":["group_theory"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Group theory","Nilpotent groups","Properties of groups"],"headings":["Definition","Examples","Explanation of term","Properties","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/8/9/5899f2389b193d11674067949f20983b.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/f/d/3fd17a2ea99592529475e6775c1f915b.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/2/a/d2a3ef341f5d5d5f83ec23583748dc4e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/7/3/b73ca3306405f610ccc2915bf0f504b8.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/d/d/9dd4e461268c8034f5c8564e155c67a6.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/f/c/dfcf28d0734569a6a693bc8194de62bf.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/0/f/a0fdddd97088690aef92440071916e39.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["order","group_theory"]],"members":["order"],"related":["Group_theory","Abelian_group","Solvable_group","Supersolvable_group","Galois_theory","Lie_group","Lie_algebra","Lie_bracket_of_vector_fields","Central_series","Central_series","Lower_central_series","Upper_central_serie